label.value: Loss of Patency of Side Branch

value.value: A decrease in the openness of a side branch of a blood vessel.

label.value: Loss of Patency of Major Vessel

value.value: A decrease in the openness of a major, or great, blood vessel.
That treatment of vessel disease or injury by dialysis, operative procedures, or device placement.

label.value: New Loss of Viable Myocardium by Non-invasive Imaging Technique

value.value: A finding of loss of viable myocardium, which is new compared to prior non-invasive imaging techniques.

label.value: New Regional Wall Motion Abnormality by Non-invasive Imaging Technique

value.value: A finding of decreased regional heart wall motion contractility, which is new compared to prior non-invasive imaging techniques.

label.value: Heart Failure by Non-invasive Diagnostic Technique

value.value: A finding of heart failure through a non-invasive diagnostic technique.
Abnormal breath sounds (crackles) heard on auscultation, indicating inflammation, fluid, or infection of the lung.
Imaging findings consistent with increased intravascular blood volume in the lungs.
Any new or worsening ST or T wave changes present in two or more contiguous leads that occur when a patient is experiencing neither physical nor chemical stressors.
A finding of decreased blood flow in the microcirculation of the heart.

label.value: Joint Task Force Type 1 Myocardial Infarction

value.value: Spontaneous myocardial infarction related to ischaemia due to a primary coronary event such as plaque erosion and/or rupture, fissuring, or dissection. (Universal definition of myocardial infarction, Kristian Thygesen, Joseph S. Alpert and Harvey D. White on behalf of the Joint ESC/ACCF/AHA/WHF Task Force for the Redefinition of Myocardial Infarction, Eur Heart J (2007) 28 (20): 2525-2538.)

label.value: Joint Task Force Type 2 Myocardial Infarction

value.value: Myocardial infarction secondary to ischaemia due to either increased oxygen demand or decreased supply, e.g. coronary artery spasm, coronary embolism, anaemia, arrhythmias, hypertension, or hypotension. (Universal definition of myocardial infarction, Kristian Thygesen, Joseph S. Alpert and Harvey D. White on behalf of the Joint ESC/ACCF/AHA/WHF Task Force for the Redefinition of Myocardial Infarction, Eur Heart J (2007) 28 (20): 2525-2538.)

label.value: Joint Task Force Type 3 Myocardial Infarction

value.value: Sudden unexpected cardiac death, including cardiac arrest, often with symptoms suggestive of myocardial ischaemia, accompanied by presumably new ST elevation, or new LBBB, or evidence of fresh thrombus in a coronary artery by angiography and/or at autopsy, but death occurring before blood samples could be obtained, or at a time before the appearance of cardiac biomarkers in the blood. (Universal definition of myocardial infarction, Kristian Thygesen, Joseph S. Alpert and Harvey D. White on behalf of the Joint ESC/ACCF/AHA/WHF Task Force for the Redefinition of Myocardial Infarction, Eur Heart J (2007) 28 (20): 2525-2538.)

label.value: Joint Task Force Type 4A Myocardial Infarction

value.value: Myocardial infarction associated with PCI. (Universal definition of myocardial infarction, Kristian Thygesen, Joseph S. Alpert and Harvey D. White on behalf of the Joint ESC/ACCF/AHA/WHF Task Force for the Redefinition of Myocardial Infarction, Eur Heart J (2007) 28 (20): 2525-2538.)

label.value: Joint Task Force Type 4B Myocardial Infarction

value.value: Myocardial infarction associated with stent thrombosis as documented by angiography or at autopsy. (Universal definition of myocardial infarction, Kristian Thygesen, Joseph S. Alpert and Harvey D. White on behalf of the Joint ESC/ACCF/AHA/WHF Task Force for the Redefinition of Myocardial Infarction, Eur Heart J (2007) 28 (20): 2525-2538.)

label.value: Joint Task Force Type 4C Myocardial Infarction

value.value: Myocardial infarction associated with stent restenosis as detected by coronary angiography or at autopsy. (Universal definition of myocardial infarction, Kristian Thygesen, Joseph S. Alpert and Harvey D. White on behalf of the Joint ESC/ACCF/AHA/WHF Task Force for the Redefinition of Myocardial Infarction, Eur Heart J (2007) 28 (20): 2525-2538.)

label.value: Joint Task Force Type 5 Myocardial Infarction

value.value: Myocardial infarction associated with CABG. (Universal definition of myocardial infarction, Kristian Thygesen, Joseph S. Alpert and Harvey D. White on behalf of the Joint ESC/ACCF/AHA/WHF Task Force for the Redefinition of Myocardial Infarction, Eur Heart J (2007) 28 (20): 2525-2538.)

label.value: ER or Office Visit Due to Heart Failure

value.value: A finding of heart failure during a visit to the emergency room or a doctor's office.
A finding of a worsening decrease in blood supply to the vital organs.

label.value: Coronary Artery Thrombosis Method of Identification

value.value: The method used to detect a coronary artery thrombus.
An indication as to whether the event meets the criteria for a clinical endpoint.
A classification or description of the visit by a patient or study participant to a medical professional.

label.value: Lab Findings of New or Worsening Heart Failure

value.value: A description of the clinical, laboratory or molecular evidence of heart failure that can be classified as new or worsening.

label.value: Physical Examination Findings of New or Worsening Heart Failure

value.value: A description of the physical examination evidence of heart failure that can be classified as new or worsening.
A classification or description of the therapeutic agent or procedure that is being escalated.
An indication as to whether the subject has symptoms of ischemic discomfort.
A classification or description of the evidence of ischemia in the subject.

label.value: Exclusion of Type 1 and Type 2 Myocardial Infarction Diagnosis Indicator

value.value: An indication as to whether type 1 and type 2 myocardial infarction is excluded as a diagnosis.
The subjective evidence of disease perceived by the patient that can be classified as new or worsening

label.value: Acute Myocardial Infarction From PCI Complication Type

value.value: A description of the complications from a percutaneous coronary intervention procedure that lead to an acute myocardial ischemic event.
An indication as to whether the procedure is considered successful.
An indication as to whether the subject had symptoms related to the clinical event of interest.
The date and time on which the symptoms began or were first noted.

label.value: Vessel Occlusion 48 Hours after CABG Indicator

value.value: An indication as to whether vessel occlusion occurred 48 hours after a coronary artery bypass graft procedure
An electrocardiographic recording that does not demonstrate any significant signs of ischemia or conduction abnormalities.

The measure of an individual's cardiac output as divided by their body surface area (CI= CO/BSA). This calculation is a useful function to determine an individual's cardiac performance in relation to their body size, providing an overview of global cardiovascular function.

The total volume of blood pumped by the heart over a set period of time, conventionally one minute; it is calculated as heart rate times stroke volume (CO= HR x SV), and is additionally dependent on preload and afterload for functional output.

The resistance to blood flow offered by the pulmonary vasculature, which is normally one sixth of SVR. The major determinant of PVR is pulmonary vessel constriction, most often caused by hypoxia and/or hypercarbia. Prolonged elevated PVR can cause right heart failure.

The resistance to blood flow offered by all systemic vasculature, excluding pulmonary vasculature. The major determinant of SVR is arteriolar tone, but blood viscosity and vascular capacitance are also contributing factors.

label.value: Atrial Tachycardia With AV Block by ECG Finding

value.value: An electrocardiographic recording that demonstrates atrial tachycardia without 1:1 atrioventricular conduction.
An electrocardiographic recording that demonstrates an R-R interval that exceeds a predefined duration threshold, irrespective of the underlying rhythm.

label.value: Pause Greater Than Three Seconds by ECG Finding

value.value: An electrocardiographic recording that demonstrates an R-R interval that exceeds three seconds, irrespective of the underlying rhythm.
An electrocardiographic recording that demonstrates two sequential premature atrial complexes.
An electrocardiographic measurement of the maximum number of atrial depolarizations (P waves) recorded during a specified period of time, and usually expressed in beats per minute.
An assessment of the median atrial depolarization rate as measured and recorded by an electrocardiograph during a specified period of time, and which is usually expressed in beats per minute.
An electrocardiographic measurement of the minimum rate of atrial depolarizations (P waves) recorded during a specified period of time, and usually expressed in beats per minute.
